Capstone Project for DTSC 691¶

Eastern University¶

Food Desert analysis for the greater Pittsburgh area¶

The goal of this final project is to determine which factors and which classification model best predict food desert status for Allegheny County. The USDA defines a food desert as an area which is both low income and low access to healthy food options. The area of measurement for all of these datasets will be the census tract. For this research, I chose a food desert indicator where the census tract is low income and 1 mile away from healthy food in urban areas and 10 miles away in rural areas. All of Allegheny county is considered an urban area due to its cities' promixity to Pittsburgh.

Data Description¶

A 20 feature data frame will be created with the significant values from each of these datasets¶

All of the following datasets were obtained from the Western Pennsylvania Regional Data Center, all data representing 2016 unless otherwise noted:¶

  • Obesity Rates 2006-2010 (.csv)
  • Diabetes and Hypertension comorbidity (.csv)
    • the diabetes/hypertension dataset was in the form of count of total insured VS count of individuals diagnosed diabetes and hypertension
  • 2016 Allegheny County Census Tracts (.geojson)
    • imported this data because it contains the abbreviated census tract which matches the obesity/diabetes/hypertension (health) dataframe
    • it also contains the geometry information which allows me merge the health dataframe with it and plot a choropleth map corresponding to the rate of obesity or diabetes and hypertension
  • Fast Food Restaurant Locations in Allegheny County (.geojson)
    • contains the latitude and longitude point of each "fast food" restaurant in Allegheny county
    • fast food, here, is considered a "chain restaurant which does not serve alcohol"
  • Supermarkets and Convenience Stores in Allegheny County (.geojson)
    • contains latitude and longitude points for each supermarket and convenience store in Allegheny county
    • this dataset had some erroneous latitude/longitude values which were discovered when trying to plot the data over a map Allegheny county
  • Allegheny County Walk Scores (.csv)
    • as Pittsburgh/Allegheny county is not a very flat area, I wanted to see if there was any correlation between having a low walk score (not a viable option to walk 1 mile to the grocery store) and food desert status

From the USDA, the Food Access Research Atlas was used to incorporate multiple variables¶

  • the most important variable it contained was a label encoded food desert status column where 1 indicated a food desert census tract and 0 indicated a census tract which was not a food desert, also known as a food oasis
  • other variables it included were poverty rate, number of individuals in a certain race, median family income, individuals recieving SNAP benefits, and number of individuals over 65

From the United States Census, I exported data on educational attainment for each census tract in Allegheny County¶

  • this dataset had a huge number of columns which I narrowed down to the population of the census tract and the number of individuals who did not graduate high school, graduated high school, have an associates degree or has taken some college classes, and those who have a bachelor's degree or higher.

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(15, 15))

# import custom color scheme creator
import mapclassify as mc
scheme = mc.Quantiles(fullHealth['obesity_rate'], k=10)
## k value of 10 was chosen due to the color scheme changing to red at around 30% obesity which, at the time of
## collection of this data, was the US average obesity rate
### dark red indicating a very high percentage of the population being considered obese

gplt.choropleth(fullHealth, hue="obesity_rate", linewidth=.5, scheme=scheme,
                cmap='coolwarm', legend=True, ax=ax)

ax.set_title('Obesity Rate in Allegheny County by Census Tract', fontsize=16)

plt.show()

grocery = pd.read_csv('supermarketsalleg.csv')

# noticed some odd rows where all were NaN so I dropped them
grocery = grocery.dropna(thresh=2)

## noticed more odd values in the longitude column which did not make sense for the area I am studying
## made parameters that require all values to be within Allegheny county latitude/longitude
grocery = grocery[grocery['Lon'] < -77.5]
grocery = grocery[grocery['Lon'] > -80.4]
grocery = grocery[grocery['Lat'] > 40.2]

With this dictionary I can see I only need the following columns:¶

0-5 are self explanatory
9. LILATract_1And!0 = *food desert* low income low access 1 mile for urban area and 10 miles for rural
15. PovertyRate = poverty rate for that tract
16. MedianFamilyIncome = tract median family income 
137. TractSeniors = number of individuals over 65 in a tract
138. TractWhite = number of individuals in a tract who are white
139. TractBlack = number of individuals in a tract who are black
140. TractAsian = number of individuals in a tract who are asian
141. TractNHOPI = number of individuals in a tract who are native Hawaiian or other pacific islander
142. TractAIAN = number of individuals in a tract who are american indian or alaskan native
143. TractOMultir = number of individuals in a tract who are other or multiple races
144. TractHispanic = number of individuals in a tract who are hispanic or latino
146. TractSNAP = number of housing units receiving SNAP benefits

Obesity and diabetes/hypertension rates dataframe and the Allegheny county FARA dataframe need to now be merged¶

They both have the column have the same full census tract column which in common which will make a merge more simple, after the column names are changed to be equal.

I ran into an issue when merging these dataframes¶

  • The resulting dataframe was 358 values where it should be 400 values
  • To fix this, I will fill NA values from the health dataframe with the mean of both the obesity rate and the diabetes/hypertension rate
In [30]:
# change GEOID column in fullHealth to CensusTract so that it matches ac dataframe
fullHealth = fullHealth.rename(columns = {'GEOID':'CensusTract'})

# the only columns I need from fullHealth are the census tracts, and obesity and diabetes/hypertension rates
factors = fullHealth[['CensusTract', 'obesity_rate', 'diabhyper_rate']]

## to be able to take the mean of each column I first need to change the data types to integers and floats
factors = factors.astype({'CensusTract':int, 'obesity_rate':float, 'diabhyper_rate':float})

### getting replacement values for the entire dataframe... many missing values in Municipality and Neighborhood
values = {'Municipality':'Pittsburgh', 'Neighborhood':'Allegheny', 'obesity':factors['obesity_rate'].mean(), 
         'diabhyper':factors['diabhyper_rate'].mean()}

ac = pd.merge(ac,factors,how='left', on='CensusTract').fillna(value=values)

We can clearly see the lack of food options in some of these food deserts¶

  • While visualization can help us understand the data, it will not tell us everything.
  • The number of food options in each census tract will need to be counted to be able to be used in the classification model.
In [35]:
# need to separate convenience stores from the grocery stores data frame because they dont carry fresh food
convenient = grocery[grocery['Category'] == 'Convenience Store']

# bad food is now all fast food and convenience stores
BADfood = gpd.GeoDataFrame(fastfood.append(convenient), geometry='geometry', crs="EPSG:4326")

# good food is now only supermarkets
GOODfood = gpd.GeoDataFrame(grocery[grocery['Category'] == 'Supermarket'],geometry='geometry',crs="EPSG:4326")

4: B23006_016E: total "some college" or associates degree
5: B23006_023E: total bachelor's degree or higher
In [43]:
# take the above mentioned columns and the extended census tract from the imported DataFrame
ed = eduattn[['GEO_ID', 'B23006_001E', 'B23006_002E', 'B23006_009E', 'B23006_016E', 'B23006_023E']]

# rename the columns
newcolumns = {'GEO_ID':'CensusTract', 'B23006_001E':'population', 'B23006_002E': 'dropout', 
              'B23006_009E':'high_school', 'B23006_016E':'associate', 'B23006_023E':'bachelor'}
ed = ed.rename(columns=newcolumns)

# need to drop the first row with the column labels
ed = ed.iloc[1:]

## walkscores had a shortened census tract and educational attainment has the extended which i will now shorten
ed['CensusTract'] = ed['CensusTract'].str[9:]

# and change all data types to integer so that mathematical operations can be performed
ed = ed.astype(int)

# perform mathematical operations
## divide counts for each census tract by the stated population
ed['dropout'] = ed['dropout'] / ed['population']
ed['high_school'] = ed['high_school'] / ed['population']
ed['associate'] = ed['associate'] / ed['population']
ed['bachelor'] = ed['bachelor'] / ed['population']

The top two most important features when determining food desert status are: median family income and poverty rate.¶

This is not a surprising finding because we know that food desert status automatically means that the area is low income. The feature that was tied in importance with median family income, is attainment of a Bachelor's degree or higher, which was observed to be of high correlation when visualizing the data with a bar plot. On the correlation heat map we saw that both Bachelor's degree and median family income were neagatively correlated with a relatively high number (around -0.25).

Three features were found to be of zero importance to this AdaBoost model: percentage of white people in the census tract, percentage of asian people, and percentage of people who only graduated high school. When visualizing the data, we saw that percentage of white people in a tract was negatively correlated with food desert status, but not by a very high number (-0.11)

The obvious answer was found to be the right one for this classification model. The most important variables when determining food desert status in Allegheny county relate to the income and poverty rate for each census tract, but the percentage of people who have a Bachelor's degree is equally as important as median family income. We can visualize the median family income with the percentages of educational attainment to see if people with a Bachelor's degree or higher are more likely to have a higher income than other attainment levels.

In Conclusion,¶

What does this tell us about food deserts?¶

In the beginning of the project, I hypothesized that indivduals in food deserts would be much more "unhealthy", meaning higher rates of obesity, diabetes, and hypertension, but that was not the case. Health factors had little to no correlation to food desert status. This tells me that people do not always resort to unhealthy food options when their healthy options are scarce. I also hypothesized that walkscores would have some importance in the model, but it was found to have little to no importance. The above pairplot confirms my final hypothesis that higher educational attainment would lead to higher median family income, thus correlating with food desert status.
